    <fr:title text="Closure of partial functions under identity and composition › "><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K8.xml" title="Closure of partial functions under identity and composition" addr="jms-00K8" type="local">Closure of <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">partial functions</fr:link> under <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00II.xml" title="The identity relation" addr="jms-00II" type="local">identity</fr:link> and <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00IN.xml" title="Relational composite" addr="jms-00IN" type="local">composition</fr:link></fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:p>First, we prove that each <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00II.xml" title="The identity relation" addr="jms-00II" type="local">identity relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {id}_{A}\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">functional</fr:link>. Fixing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a,a_1,a_2\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=a_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=a_2]]></fr:tex>, we must show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_1=a_2]]></fr:tex>; this follows from transitivity and symmetry of equality.</html:p>
 <html:p>Next, we fix <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">partial functions</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g \colon  B\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } C]]></fr:tex> to check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\circ  f \colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } C]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">functional</fr:link>. Fixing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c_1,c_2\in  C]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (g\circ  f\right )\mathclose {}}}c_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {{\mathopen {}\left (g\circ  f\right )\mathclose {}}}c_2]]></fr:tex>, we must check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c_1=c_2]]></fr:tex>. By definition of the relational composite, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b_1,b_2\in  B]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {f}b_1\mathrel {g}c_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {f}b_2\mathrel {g}c_2]]></fr:tex>. Because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B]]></fr:tex> is functional, we note that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b_1 = b_2]]></fr:tex>. Writing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b=b_1=b_2]]></fr:tex>, we therefore have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\mathrel {g}c_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\mathrel {g}c_2]]></fr:tex>. Because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  B\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } C]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00K7.xml" title="Partial function" addr="jms-00K7" type="local">functional</fr:link>, we conclude that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c_1=c_2]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
