            <fr:title text="Partial function">Partial function</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } B]]></fr:tex> is said to be <html:em><html:strong>functional</html:strong></html:em> when it relates an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <html:em>at most</html:em> one element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>:</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \forall  a\in  A\mathpunct {.}
 \forall  b_1,b_2\in  B\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {R}b_1\land  a\mathrel {R}b_2
 \implies 
 b_1 = b_2
]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>We refer to a functional <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> as a <html:em><html:strong>partial function</html:strong></html:em>; we often use letters like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f,g]]></fr:tex> to refer to partial functions rather than <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R,S]]></fr:tex>. When we write <html:span style="white-space: nowrap">“<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex>”</html:span>, we mean that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is a partial function from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
              <fr:contributor>
                <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
              </fr:contributor>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>1</fr:month>
              <fr:day>17</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:addr>jms-00II</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00II.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="The identity relation">The identity <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>For any set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we can form the <html:em><html:strong>identity <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link></html:strong></html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {id}_{A}\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex>, also called the <html:em><html:strong>equality <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link></html:strong></html:em>, which relates each element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to itself. In other words, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {\mathsf {id}_{A}} a']]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a=a']]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
